{
  "intro": {
    "title": "Quantifiers",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "What quantifiers do (core logic)",
        "content": "Quantifiers answer **how much?** or **how many?** before a noun — they sit in the same slot as articles (a / the): ONE determiner per noun phrase.\n- Determiners inside the Noun Phrase root (#3 in the Tree Model) — every time you talk about an amount (food, time, people, money) you need one.\n- The biggest split is **countable vs uncountable**: most quantifiers prefer one or the other. Mix them up and the sentence is just wrong — ~~much books~~ is broken English, not a small mistake.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "groups": [
              {
                "label": "countable",
                "items": [
                  "book",
                  "friend",
                  "idea"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "uncountable",
                "items": [
                  "water",
                  "time",
                  "advice"
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "decision",
            "title": "Key principle — ask first, then choose",
            "steps": [
              {
                "q": "Is the noun countable (*book, friend, idea*)?",
                "yes": "choose a countable quantifier"
              },
              {
                "end": "uncountable (*water, time, advice*) — choose an uncountable quantifier"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "some / any",
        "content": "The **default pair** — an unspecified amount or number. Both work with countable AND uncountable nouns.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "comparison",
            "left": {
              "title": "some — positive, offers, requests",
              "points": [
                "I have **some** milk.",
                "Would you like **some** tea?",
                "Can I have **some** water?"
              ]
            },
            "right": {
              "title": "any — negatives, questions",
              "points": [
                "I don't have **any** money.",
                "Do you have **any** time?"
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "I bought **some** bread.",
                "why": "positive"
              },
              {
                "good": "I didn't buy **any** bread.",
                "why": "negative"
              },
              {
                "good": "Did you buy **any** bread?",
                "why": "genuine question"
              },
              {
                "good": "Would you like **some** bread?",
                "why": "offer — expecting yes"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "style": "cz",
            "text": "Czech speakers often drop these (*Mám mléko* → *I have milk*). English usually needs *some* or *any* with plural or uncountable nouns — missing them sounds like a beginner; the wrong one (*I have any milk*) sounds broken."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A1"
      },
      {
        "title": "much / many / a lot of",
        "content": "The big three for large amounts — this is where countable vs uncountable matters most.\nReal conversations and exam writing both turn on this.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "much / many / a lot of",
            "headers": [
              "Quantifier",
              "Use with",
              "Typical context",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**much**",
                "Uncountable",
                "Negatives, questions",
                "not much time, how much money?"
              ],
              [
                "**many**",
                "Countable plural",
                "Positives, negatives, questions",
                "many books, not many people, how many?"
              ],
              [
                "**a lot of / lots of**",
                "Both",
                "Positives (most natural)",
                "a lot of friends, lots of water"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "I don't have **much** time. How **much** sugar?"
              },
              {
                "good": "**Many** people agree. There aren't **many** seats."
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **a lot of** friends. There's **a lot of** traffic."
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **a lot of** time.",
                "bad": "I have much time.",
                "why": "*much* in positive statements sounds formal or unnatural — use **a lot of**"
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **a lot of** friends.",
                "bad": "I have much friends.",
                "why": "Czech-speaker trap — double error: *much* + countable"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A2.quantifiers.much_many_a_lot"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      },
      {
        "title": "(a) few / (a) little",
        "content": "The small-amount pair — and one small word (**a**) flips the meaning from positive to negative.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "The attitude shift",
            "headers": [
              "Form",
              "With",
              "Meaning",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**a few**",
                "countable",
                "= some (positive feeling)",
                "I have **a few** friends here. (enough — happy)"
              ],
              [
                "**few**",
                "countable",
                "almost none (negative)",
                "He has **few** friends. (sad — lonely)"
              ],
              [
                "**a little**",
                "uncountable",
                "= some (positive)",
                "I need **a little** help. (a small amount — OK)"
              ],
              [
                "**little**",
                "uncountable",
                "almost none (negative)",
                "There's **little** hope. (almost no hope — bleak)"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "decision",
            "title": "Quick test",
            "steps": [
              {
                "q": "Do you mean *some, enough*?",
                "yes": "use **a** — a few / a little"
              },
              {
                "end": "not enough, almost none → drop **a** — few / little"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "style": "cz",
            "text": "Czech speakers often miss the *a* — *I have few time* is both grammatically wrong (countable/uncountable) and conveys hopelessness when you just meant 'a small amount'."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A2.quantifiers.few_little"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      },
      {
        "title": "all / most / no / none",
        "content": "The degree scale — from 100% down to 0%.\n*no* and *none* mean the same thing but work differently in the sentence — mix them up and the grammar breaks.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "The degree scale",
            "headers": [
              "Quantifier",
              "Meaning",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**all**",
                "100% — the whole amount/group",
                "**All** students passed. **All** the water is gone."
              ],
              [
                "**most**",
                "the majority",
                "**Most** people agree. **Most** of the time it works."
              ],
              [
                "**some**",
                "an unspecified part",
                "see the some / any card"
              ],
              [
                "**no** + noun",
                "zero — needs a noun after it",
                "I have **no** time. There are **no** seats."
              ],
              [
                "**none**",
                "zero — stands alone, or *none of*",
                "**None** of them came. How many left? **None**."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "**No** students came. / **None of the** students came.",
                "bad": "None students came.",
                "why": "*no* + noun; *none* alone or + *of the*"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      },
      {
        "title": "both / either / neither (exactly two)",
        "content": "A separate small system for exactly TWO things. With three or more, switch to *all / any / none* — using *both* for three things is a giveaway error.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "table",
            "title": "Exactly two",
            "headers": [
              "Word",
              "Meaning",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "**both**",
                "the two together",
                "**Both** answers are correct. I like **both** of them."
              ],
              [
                "**either**",
                "one or the other",
                "You can sit on **either** side. Take **either** one."
              ],
              [
                "**neither**",
                "not one and not the other",
                "**Neither** answer is right. I like **neither** of them."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "text": "Verb agreement: *both* takes plural (*Both are correct*); *neither* + singular noun takes singular (*Neither answer **is** right*)."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B1"
      },
      {
        "title": "Common Czech-speaker errors",
        "content": "High-frequency mistakes — they appear in every speaking exam, every email, every conversation about quantities.\nFixing them gives immediate visible progress.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "**a lot of** friends",
                "bad": "much friends",
                "why": "countable, positive"
              },
              {
                "good": "**much / a lot of** water",
                "bad": "many water",
                "why": "uncountable"
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **a little** time.",
                "bad": "I have few time.",
                "why": "uncountable + positive"
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **some** money.",
                "bad": "I have any money.",
                "why": "positive statement"
              },
              {
                "good": "I have **some** money.",
                "why": "bare *I have money* (no quantifier) often needs *some* in English"
              },
              {
                "good": "**No** students came. / **None of the** students came.",
                "bad": "None students came."
              },
              {
                "good": "**fewer** people",
                "bad": "less people",
                "why": "countable → *fewer*; uncountable → *less*"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any",
          "A2.quantifiers.much_many_a_lot",
          "A2.quantifiers.few_little",
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Practice roadmap & next steps",
        "content": "Direct practice in this curriculum — start here after the cards:\n- Guided MC (some/any, much/many, few/little)\n- Gap fill (mixed quantifiers in context)\n- Error correction (the typical traps)\n\nFor the noun side of this — when a noun is *countable* vs *uncountable* in the first place — see [[topic:countable_uncountable|Countable & Uncountable Nouns]]. For the other half of determiners, see [[topic:articles|Articles (a/an/the)]].",
        "root_ids": [
          "A1.quantifiers.some_any",
          "A2.quantifiers.much_many_a_lot",
          "A2.quantifiers.few_little",
          "B1.quantifiers.all_most_none"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "A2"
      }
    ]
  },
  "check": {
    "title": "Test your understanding",
    "questions": [
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'I have _____ milk.' (positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "some",
          "b": "any",
          "c": "much",
          "d": "many"
        },
        "correct_option": "a",
        "explanation": "Positive statement with uncountable → some."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'How _____ books did you read?' Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "much",
          "b": "many",
          "c": "some",
          "d": "little"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Books = countable → many."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'She has _____ friends.' (a small number, positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "few",
          "b": "a few",
          "c": "little",
          "d": "a little"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Friends = countable; positive (some) → a few."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'There isn't _____ time.' Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "some",
          "b": "any",
          "c": "many",
          "d": "few"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Negative → any."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "'I need _____ help.' (a small amount, positive) Which fits?",
        "options": {
          "a": "little",
          "b": "a little",
          "c": "few",
          "d": "a few"
        },
        "correct_option": "b",
        "explanation": "Help = uncountable; positive → a little."
      }
    ]
  },
  "practice_order": [
    "gapfill",
    "errorcorrection"
  ],
  "practice": {
    "gapfill": {
      "title": "Practice: Choose the correct quantifier",
      "questions": [
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "I have _____ milk in the fridge.",
          "options": {
            "a": "some",
            "b": "any",
            "c": "many",
            "d": "few"
          },
          "correct_option": "a",
          "explanation": "Positive, uncountable → some."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "Do you have _____ sugar?",
          "options": {
            "a": "some",
            "b": "any",
            "c": "much",
            "d": "many"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Question → any."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "How _____ people were at the party?",
          "options": {
            "a": "much",
            "b": "many",
            "c": "some",
            "d": "little"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Countable (people) → many."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "She has _____ friends in London.",
          "options": {
            "a": "few",
            "b": "a few",
            "c": "little",
            "d": "a little"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Countable, positive (some) → a few."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "There is _____ water left. (almost none)",
          "options": {
            "a": "little",
            "b": "a little",
            "c": "few",
            "d": "a few"
          },
          "correct_option": "a",
          "explanation": "Uncountable, negative (almost none) → little."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "We have _____ time to finish. (some)",
          "options": {
            "a": "little",
            "b": "a little",
            "c": "many",
            "d": "much"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Uncountable, positive (some) → a little."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "_____ the students passed the exam.",
          "options": {
            "a": "All",
            "b": "Most",
            "c": "No",
            "d": "Any"
          },
          "correct_option": "a",
          "explanation": "The whole group → all."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "I don't have _____ money.",
          "options": {
            "a": "some",
            "b": "any",
            "c": "many",
            "d": "few"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Negative → any."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "There are _____ apples on the table. (a small number)",
          "options": {
            "a": "few",
            "b": "a few",
            "c": "little",
            "d": "a little"
          },
          "correct_option": "b",
          "explanation": "Countable, positive → a few."
        },
        {
          "type": "mc",
          "question": "He has _____ experience in teaching.",
          "options": {
            "a": "much",
            "b": "many",
            "c": "a lot of",
            "d": "few"
          },
          "correct_option": "c",
          "explanation": "Positive statement, uncountable → a lot of."
        }
      ]
    },
    "errorcorrection": {
      "title": "Practice: Correct the quantifier",
      "questions": [
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'I have any milk.' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "I have some milk.",
            "I have some milk"
          ],
          "explanation": "Positive → some, not any."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'How much books did you read?' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "How many books did you read?",
            "How many books did you read"
          ],
          "explanation": "Books = countable → many."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'She has few friends.' (meaning she has some friends) Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "She has a few friends.",
            "She has a few friends"
          ],
          "explanation": "Positive (some) → a few."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'I need a little eggs.' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "I need a few eggs.",
            "I need a few eggs"
          ],
          "explanation": "Eggs = countable → a few."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'There isn't some bread.' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "There isn't any bread.",
            "There isn't any bread"
          ],
          "explanation": "Negative → any."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'How many water do you need?' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "How much water do you need?",
            "How much water do you need"
          ],
          "explanation": "Water = uncountable → much."
        },
        {
          "type": "open",
          "question": "Wrong: 'Less and less people are using public transport.' Correct the sentence.",
          "answers": [
            "Fewer and fewer people are using public transport.",
            "Fewer and fewer people are using public transport"
          ],
          "explanation": "People is countable → use **fewer**, not **less**. **Less** is for uncountable nouns (less time, less water); **fewer** is for countable nouns (fewer people, fewer books)."
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
